body:
I ran into an issue recently when attempting to get particular child components, and I noticed something interesting...

It seems that the order in which this.props.children is populated is based on execution time of each component, and not the actual order in which they are positioned.

Let me give you an example:

``` html
<MainComponent>
    <h1>Hello <b>World</b></h1>

    <p>Hello world!</p>
</MainComponent>
```

The current method I'm using to try and grab the `<h1>` element is by using `this.props.children.pop()`. The expectation (since `this.props.children` is an array) is that the first element in the array would be the `<h1>` tag. However, since there are other components inside of the `<h1>`, it is added to the array after the `<p>` regardless of the order in which it is declared.

I understand that **React** provides ways of manipulating the children via `React.Children`, however, there's no real method of differentiating between certain children without it being cumbersome.

**This:**

``` javascript
var heading = this.props.children.pop();
```

**Turns into this:**

``` javascript
var heading;

React.Children.map(this.props.children, function(child){
    if(!heading && child.displayName === "h1") {
        heading = child;
    }

    return child;
});
```

Maybe providing some sort of interface to search/retrieve specific children using `React.Children` may be beneficial? Something like `React.Children.getByDisplayName('h1')` or similar?

Because `React.Children.map` requires a callback (and as such, is not entirely portable), this is a bit cumbersome to pull out and put into a mixin or utility object for my own reuse without having to copy/paste these 7 lines into every component that I would like to retrieve specific children for.

I apologize if there are already resources within **React** to do this (or maybe a methodology to follow instead). In my searching, I was not able to find anything.
